# Why Do People Want to Overturn Roe v. Wade? A Comprehensive Analysis

The landmark 1973 Supreme Court decision in *Roe v. Wade* established a constitutional right to abortion in the United States, profoundly shaping American legal, social, and political landscapes. However, the decision has been a subject of intense debate and division for nearly five decades. This report explores the multifaceted reasons why a significant segment of the American population and political actors advocate for overturning *Roe v. Wade*. Drawing on a wide range of sources, including polling data, legal analyses, and opinion pieces, this report provides a detailed, objective, and comprehensive examination of the arguments and motivations behind the push to overturn *Roe*.

---

## 1. Overview of Public Opinion on Roe v. Wade

Before delving into the reasons for wanting to overturn *Roe*, it is important to understand the public opinion landscape. Polls consistently show that a majority of Americans oppose overturning *Roe v. Wade*, but there is also substantial support for certain abortion restrictions and for returning abortion regulation to the states.

For example, a 2021 Gallup poll found that 58% of Americans opposed overturning *Roe*, while 32% favored it ([Gallup, 2021](https://news.gallup.com/poll/350804/americans-opposed-overturning-roe-wade.aspx)). Similarly, a 2019 Pew Research Center survey reported that 70% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to completely overturn *Roe* ([Pew Research Center, 2019](https://www.pewresearch.org/politics/2019/08/29/u-s-public-continues-to-favor-legal-abortion-oppose-overturning-roe-v-wade/)).

However, support varies significantly by political affiliation and ideological leanings. Republicans tend to be more divided, with about half favoring overturning *Roe* and half opposing it, while Democrats overwhelmingly oppose overturning the decision. Additionally, many Americans who oppose overturning *Roe* also support certain abortion restrictions, such as bans after fetal heartbeat detection or waiting periods ([Gallup, 2021](https://news.gallup.com/poll/350804/americans-opposed-overturning-roe-wade.aspx); [FiveThirtyEight, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/most-americans-dont-want-roe-v-wade-repealed-but-many-also-support-restrictions-on-abortion/)).

