## 2. Legal and Constitutional Arguments Against Roe v. Wade

### 2.1 Roeâ€™s Legal Foundation is Considered Indefensible

One of the primary reasons cited for overturning *Roe* is the belief that the decision lacks a solid constitutional foundation. Critics argue that *Roe* was a judicial overreach that created a constitutional right to abortion without clear textual or historical basis in the Constitution. For instance, legal scholars Carter Snead and Richard Garnett describe *Roe* as "indefensible," emphasizing that it established a right that has no basis in the Constitution ([LifeNews, 2021](https://www.lifenews.com/2021/12/16/five-reasons-why-the-supreme-court-should-overturn-roe-v-wade/)).

Furthermore, the legal basis for *Roe* has already been altered by subsequent Supreme Court rulings, such as *Planned Parenthood v. Casey* (1992), which shifted the rationale from privacy rights to liberty rights. This shift is seen by some as evidence that *Roe* was unstable and ripe for reconsideration ([The Imaginative Conservative, 2021](https://theimaginativeconservative.org/2021/10/eight-reasons-overturn-roe-v-wade-thomas-ascik.html)).

### 2.2 Roe is Outdated and Out of Step with Modern Legal Standards

Critics argue that *Roe* was decided in a very different social and legal context and that many of its premises no longer hold. For example, the role of women in society has dramatically changed since 1973, with women achieving significant political and professional milestones that challenge the assumptions underlying *Roe* ([LifeNews, 2021](https://www.lifenews.com/2021/12/16/five-reasons-why-the-supreme-court-should-overturn-roe-v-wade/)).

Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg herself criticized *Roe* for venturing too far and presenting an incomplete justification for its action, suggesting that the decision was legally and constitutionally flawed even from a liberal judicial perspective ([The Imaginative Conservative, 2021](https://theimaginativeconservative.org/2021/10/eight-reasons-overturn-roe-v-wade-thomas-ascik.html)).

### 2.3 The Principle of Federalism and State Sovereignty

Another core argument is that *Roe* improperly removed abortion regulation from the states, imposing a federal constitutional mandate that overrides state laws. Advocates for overturning *Roe* argue that abortion policy should be decided by individual states, reflecting the preferences of their populations rather than a one-size-fits-all federal standard ([LifeNews, 2021](https://www.lifenews.com/2021/12/16/five-reasons-why-the-supreme-court-should-overturn-roe-v-wade/)).

This view holds that returning abortion regulation to the states respects the constitutional principle of federalism and allows for more democratic and localized decision-making.

