## 3. Moral and Ethical Considerations

### 3.1 The Moral Status of the Unborn Child

A fundamental reason for opposing *Roe* is the belief that life begins at fertilization and that abortion constitutes the taking of an innocent human life. This moral perspective is central to the pro-life movement and underpins many arguments for overturning *Roe* ([Daily Signal, 2021](https://www.dailysignal.com/2021/12/01/why-these-21-americans-say-supreme-court-should-overturn-roe-v-wade/)).

Opponents of *Roe* argue that the decision pits mothers against their unborn children, creating an untenable moral conflict. They contend that the law should protect the dignity and rights of both women and their unborn children, rather than prioritizing one at the expense of the other ([LifeNews, 2021](https://www.lifenews.com/2021/12/16/five-reasons-why-the-supreme-court-should-overturn-roe-v-wade/)).

### 3.2 The Impact of Roe on Society and Public Morality

Critics also argue that *Roe* has had a corrosive effect on American society by normalizing abortion on demand and undermining respect for human life. They claim that the decision has polarized the country and hindered meaningful public debate on abortion, leaving legislatures uncertain about how to regulate the practice ([The Imaginative Conservative, 2021](https://theimaginativeconservative.org/2021/10/eight-reasons-overturn-roe-v-wade-thomas-ascik.html)).

